
Linux Threat Detection 2 — TryHackMe
SOC-Focused Walkthrough Notes
Executive Summary

This lab focuses on Linux threat detection using:

System enumeration commands

Process inspection

Script analysis

SSH brute-force detection

Audit log investigation

Process execution tracing

Cryptominer activity detection

The investigation simulates a real-world Linux compromise involving SSH brute force, suspicious downloads, EDR evasion checks, lateral scanning, and cryptomining.

1️⃣ Environment & System Enumeration
Detect Cloud Environment

Command:

systemd-detect-virt

Output:

amazon

Why it matters

Confirms the host is running in AWS

Cloud context is important for IR (IAM roles, exposed services, security groups)

2️⃣ Process Inspection — EDR Detection
Look for EDR / Antivirus Processes

Command:

ps aux

Look for suspicious or security-related binaries.

Detected antimalware binary:

/var/lib/ultrasec/malscan

Why it matters

Attackers often enumerate EDR tools before executing payloads

/var/lib/ultrasec/malscan indicates a security agent is installed

3️⃣ Script Analysis & Command Tracing
Identify Script That Ran hostname

Using process investigation and reviewing scripts:

Script path:

/home/itsupport/debug.sh

To inspect the script:

sudo cat /home/itsupport/debug.sh
Last Discovery Command Launched by Script

Found inside debug.sh:

ps -eo pid,ppid,cmd,%mem,%cpu --sort=-%cpu

Why it matters

This is a reconnaissance command

Lists running processes sorted by CPU usage

Common attacker discovery technique

Script Author Email

Inside the script:

greg@tryhackme.thm

Useful for:

Attribution

Insider threat validation

Legit vs malicious script assessment

4️⃣ Suspicious Downloads & Payload Analysis
Elastic Agent Download Source

Domain:

artifacts.elastic.co

To verify downloads:

grep -i elastic /var/log/auth.log
grep -i elastic /var/log/syslog
Downloaded Helper Script Path
/var/tmp/helper.sh

Temporary directories (/tmp, /var/tmp) are common staging areas.

To check:

ls -la /var/tmp/
cat /var/tmp/helper.sh
Which Download Is More Likely Malicious?

Between curl and wget downloads:

Answer:

curl

Why

Curl was associated with suspicious behavior

Attackers often use curl for direct payload execution

5️⃣ SSH Brute Force Detection
Identify Attacker IP

Check failed SSH logins:

grep "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log

Attacker IP:

45.9.148.125

Why it matters

Multiple failed attempts from one IP = brute force

Should be blocked immediately in production

6️⃣ Post-Compromise Reconnaissance
Command Used to List Last Logged-In Users

Command:

last

Attackers use last to:

See active accounts

Identify admin users

Understand login patterns

7️⃣ EDR Enumeration via Audit Logs
Which EDR Processes Were Searched With egrep?

Command used to investigate:

grep "egrep" /var/log/audit/audit.log

Processes searched:

ds_agent,falcon,sentinel

These correspond to:

Trend Micro (ds_agent)

CrowdStrike Falcon

SentinelOne

Why it matters

Clear defense-evasion behavior

Attacker checking for security tooling

8️⃣ Malicious File Transfer via SCP
Malicious Archive Name

Using audit log:

ausearch -i -if /home/ubuntu/scenario/audit.log | grep PROCTITLE

Archive transferred:

kernupd.tar.gz

Why it matters

File name mimics kernel update

Classic disguise technique

9️⃣ Cryptominer Execution
Full Command Line of Miner Launch

Found via audit logs:

nohup /tmp/.apt/kernupd/kernupd

Indicators:

Executed from /tmp

Hidden directory .apt

Used nohup for persistence

To detect:

ausearch -i | grep kernupd
🔟 Internal Network Scanning
SSH Scan Range

From audit logs:

10.10.12.1–10.10.12.10

To locate:

ausearch -i | grep ssh

Why it matters

Indicates lateral movement attempt

Internal recon phase

High severity in enterprise environments

Key Detection Techniques Used

systemd-detect-virt → environment awareness

ps aux → process inspection

grep on auth logs → brute-force detection

Script review → command tracing

ausearch -i → audit log analysis

Process execution tracing → cryptominer detection

Network range extraction → lateral movement detection

Final SOC Takeaways

Always check SSH logs first in Linux compromises

Attackers enumerate EDR before deploying payloads

/tmp and /var/tmp are high-risk execution paths

Audit logs provide command-line ground truth

Internal scanning is a major escalation indicator

Cryptominers often use nohup and hidden directories

